Multivariate Invert Analysis

Nick Toimieri

1 Import and manipulate data

  • For INVERT data I converted NAs (in wide format) to zeros. This is a bit problematic because it looks like barnacles and sponges were not counted in 2015.

2 SWATH INVERTS

3 Year by Site by Depth (zone) nMDS

The stress for the nMDS including data averaged by year, site and depth was pretty good at stress = 0.14.

## 
## Call:
## metaMDS(comm = invert_YSD, distance = "bray", k = 2, autotransform = TRUE) 
## 
## global Multidimensional Scaling using monoMDS
## 
## Data:     invert_YSD 
## Distance: bray 
## 
## Dimensions: 2 
## Stress:     0.1376484 
## Stress type 1, weak ties
## Two convergent solutions found after 20 tries
## Scaling: centring, PC rotation, halfchange scaling 
## Species: expanded scores based on 'invert_YSD'

nMDS ordination plot of mean invert abudnace by site x year x depth zone. Closed circles = 5 m, open circles = 10 m.

4 Constrained Ordinations - Just for fun

4.1 Basic - Discriminat CAP Site x Depth x Year

4.1.1 Permanova

I did two PerManova. Both include year, site, and depth. The first includes only a subset of the invert, which were counted on at least 20 transects. The second includes all invert groups. The results are fairly similar. I would just use the all invert results.

5 Univariate Plots

These are plots of the species involved. I think we need to break out a few of these larger groups. For exmaple, we should do urchins by species not as one big lumped group. Same for some of the seastars, esp Pycnopodia and Pisaster.

Invert abundance by site and year.
